# Agent suggestions (self-learning inbox)

You improve by **proposing**, not by editing User (or Project) Cursor rules, skills, or commands directly. The human promotes what matters.

## Where to write

Under the project:

```
.cursor/suggestions/
  rules/      — behavior, conventions, when/how to work
  skills/     — multi-step workflows, domain procedures
  commands/   — shell/CLI, Cursor commands, tool invocation patterns
```

Create or update a `.md` file there. Use a short kebab-case slug (`wrong-python-env.md`). One topic per file.

## File format

```markdown
# Observation
What happened (correction, failure, pattern).

# Proposed change
Concrete text or action to adopt. Say if it should become a **global User Rule**, **project rule**, **personal skill** (`~/.cursor/skills/`), **project skill** (`.cursor/skills/`), or **Cursor command** — the human decides scope.
```

No frontmatter. Keep it short; extra detail is fine when the case is subtle.

## When to write (do write)

**Explicit signals**
- User says remember, always, never, from now on, you were wrong, don’t do that again, or asks to capture a lesson.
- User rejects your approach and gives a different one that would help in future sessions.

**Corrections and gaps**
- You violated or missed an existing User Rule or project rule; user fixed it — capture the gap so the inbox reflects reality.
- Same class of mistake twice in one session, or user notes you did it before.
- You assumed something about the repo/stack/env and were wrong.

**Tooling and execution**
- Command failed and the fix is reusable—not a one-off typo.

**Workflow and skills**
- Wrong step order, skipped step, or wrong subskill for the task; user corrects the pipeline.
- A workflow should be a skill but isn’t documented; existing skill is incomplete or misleading.
- Heavy steering through a multi-step task — end with one suggestion summarizing the durable workflow lesson.

**Conventions and process**
- Repo convention you missed (naming, tests, spec workflow, commit style beyond existing rules).
- Spec/design disagreement resolved — record the decision for later agents.
- Communication or output preference stated as lasting (format, language, “don’t code unless asked” clashes).

**Near-misses worth keeping**
- Almost committed secrets, ran/attempted destructive command, used wrong branch—if the lesson generalizes.

**After exploration**
- You discover a stable “how this project works” fact that isn’t in rules/skills and would save future sessions—file under `rules/` or `skills/` as appropriate.

## When not to write
- One-off typo or single-file fix with no general lesson.
- Episodic facts: this sample, this path, this ticket, this branch name for today only.
- Already covered by an existing rule/skill—unless the existing text is wrong; then propose an **edit** in Proposed change.
- Duplicate: search `.cursor/suggestions/<folder>/` for the same topic; update that file instead of adding another.
- Pure praise or “looks good” with nothing to change.

## Which folder

| Folder | Use for |
|--------|---------|
| `rules/` | Agent behavior, coding standards, review habits, when to ask vs act, project conventions |
| `skills/` | End-to-end procedures (e.g. SAXS pipeline order), when to open which SKILL.md, domain playbooks |
| `commands/` | Exact invocations: `autosaxs …`, conda python path, gh/git, make/test commands, Cursor slash commands |

When unsure, prefer `rules/` for “always/never” and `skills/` for “steps to accomplish X”.

## Boundaries
- Do not load or summarize the whole suggestions tree every chat—only when writing, deduping, or user asks.
- Do not put secrets in suggestions (tokens, passwords, API keys); use placeholders in Observation.
- When you create or update a suggestion file, tell the user in chat with the path (e.g. `.cursor/suggestions/rules/foo.md`). No need to announce every internal consideration.

## Optional end-of-session
If the session had corrections or repeated steering and nothing was filed yet, add one short suggestion capturing the main durable lesson before finishing.
